xtc.parser

Class CodeGenerator

  • java.lang.Object
    • xtc.tree.Visitor
      • xtc.parser.CodeGenerator

  • public class CodeGenerator
extends Visitor
    The code generator.

    The code generator makes the following assumptions about the intermediate language:

    • The entire grammar is contained in a single module.
    • All imported types have been registered with AST.importType(java.lang.String, java.lang.String) and all imported modules have been registered with AST.importModule(java.lang.String).
    • If the grammar references any types that may be locatable (as opposed to definitely being or not being locatable), the grammar must have a locatable property with value Boolean.TRUE.

    • If the grammar contains any generic values, the grammar must have a generic property with value Boolean.TRUE.

    • If the grammar contains any action base values, generic action value, or generic recursion values, the grammar must have a recursive property with value Boolean.TRUE.

    • Each production must be a full production and must have been annotated with the appropriate meta-data.

    • Generally, all options, repetitions, and nested ordered choices must have been desugared into equivalent productions. However, an ordered choice may appear as the last element of a sequence (that is not part of a predicate), a repetition may appear if the list of repeated expressions need not be memoized, an an option may appear if its value is not bound or depends on a single bound element.

    • The element of a repetition must be a sequence (with the last element possibly being an ordered choice; see previous assumption). If the repetition is bound, Analyzer.bind(List) must be able to capture the semantic value of the repeated element.

    • The element of a option must be a sequence (with the last element possibly being an ordered choice). If the option is bound, Analyzer.bind(List) must be able to capture the semantic value of the optional element.

    • The element of a string match must be a nonterminal.

    • The element of a FollowedBy or NotFollowedBy predicate must be a sequence.

    • All elements in a character switch must either be ordered choices or sequences. Furthermore, character switches may only appear as the last element in a sequence and not within predicates.

    $Revision: 1.294 $

      • numberOfChildren

        protected int numberOfChildren(int base,
                   List<Binding> children)
        Calculate the number of a generic node's children. This method returns the fixed number of children if none of the children has a list value, Integer.MAX_VALUE if any of the children has a non-null list value, and Integer.MIN_VALUE if any of the children has a list value that may be null.
        Parameters:
        base - The number of children not from the specified list.
        children - The list of bindings representing the children.
        Returns:
        The number of children.
